-- ── ejabberd ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$ejabberd is an open-source, Erlang-based XMPP, MQTT, and SIP server known for massive scalability, used to power large real-time messaging systems including early WhatsApp-style infrastructure and Nintendo Switch's chat network.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source / Custom$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (Community Edition); Business Edition custom-priced$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2002, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Small (ProcessOne)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$France$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$ejabberd Review 2026: Features, Pricing & Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$ejabberd is an open-source XMPP, MQTT, and SIP server built for massive scale. See 2026 features, Community vs Business Edition pricing, and top alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$ejabberd is an open-source, real-time messaging server that implements the XMPP (Extensible Messaging and Presence Protocol) standard along with MQTT for IoT messaging and SIP for voice signaling. Written in Erlang, a programming language originally built by Ericsson for fault-tolerant telecom systems, ejabberd is designed from the ground up for horizontal scalability, high availability, and clustering across multiple servers. The project was started in 2002 by Russian developer Alexey Shchepin as one of the earliest fully XMPP-compliant open-source servers. In 2005, the French company ProcessOne was founded specifically to take over long-term maintenance, commercialization, and enterprise support of ejabberd, and it has remained the project's primary steward ever since, employing much of the original core engineering team.

ejabberd's technical architecture leverages Erlang/OTP's lightweight process model and built-in distribution capabilities to support clustering, allowing a single node to handle roughly a million to two million concurrently connected users and clusters to scale to tens of millions. Its module system covers the full range of XMPP extension protocols (XEPs), including multi-user chat rooms, publish-subscribe, message archive management, and push notifications, and it can be extended through custom Erlang or Lua modules. Beyond XMPP, ejabberd bundles native MQTT broker support for IoT device messaging and SIP proxy capabilities for voice, making it usable as a general-purpose real-time communication backend rather than a chat-only server. It stores data in Mnesia (Erlang's built-in database) by default but also supports external SQL databases such as PostgreSQL and MySQL for larger deployments.

ejabberd is most famous for its role in the history of consumer messaging: WhatsApp's early server architecture was heavily influenced by and reportedly built on a modified version of ejabberd, and in 2009 researchers detected that Facebook's chat.facebook.com service was running a modified ejabberd instance. More recently, ejabberd has been used to power the friend-list and communication backend of the Nintendo Switch and has been adopted by the BBC and various telecom and IoT companies for large-scale real-time messaging infrastructure. This track record of powering some of the highest-concurrency chat systems in the world is central to ejabberd's reputation as one of the most battle-tested XMPP servers available.

ejabberd is distributed under a dual structure. The Community Edition is fully open source under the GPLv2, freely downloadable from GitHub, and usable in production without licensing fees, though it comes without a formal support contract. The Business Edition adds enterprise-oriented features such as enhanced performance modules for geo-distributed deployments, expanded mobile push capabilities, Long-Term Support (LTS) releases maintained for extended periods, and direct service-level agreements with ProcessOne's engineering team, including options for 24/7 support. ProcessOne also offers Fluux, a fully managed, ejabberd-based messaging cloud service for teams that do not want to operate their own servers. Pricing for both the Business Edition and Fluux is not publicly listed and requires contacting ProcessOne directly, following a common pattern among open-core infrastructure vendors that price based on scale, support tier, and deployment complexity.

ejabberd's target users are engineering teams building chat, presence, or real-time notification features into consumer apps, IoT platforms needing a reliable MQTT broker, and large organizations such as telecoms, gaming companies, and public broadcasters that need a proven, horizontally scalable messaging backbone. Its closest open-source competitors include Openfire (Java-based, simpler to operate but less proven at extreme scale), Prosody (lightweight, Lua-based XMPP server popular for smaller deployments), Tigase, and MongooseIM (also Erlang-based). It also competes indirectly with the newer Matrix protocol ecosystem, whose reference server Synapse and client Element offer end-to-end encryption and federation as core design principles rather than as XMPP extensions. ejabberd differentiates itself through its multi-protocol support (XMPP, MQTT, and SIP in one server), its Erlang-based fault tolerance, and an unusually long and well-documented history of running some of the largest real-time messaging deployments in the world.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '7060eb6f-8b75-4dcd-b7ed-90b63b5d8986';

