-- ── eLabFTW ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$eLabFTW is a free, open-source electronic lab notebook and inventory manager for research labs, self-hostable at no cost, with optional paid support and hosting from its maker, Deltablot.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source / Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (self-hosted); PRO support from EUR 760/year$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2012, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Small (Deltablot SASU)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Paris, France$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$French$q$, $q$German$q$, $q$Spanish$q$, $q$Chinese$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$eLabFTW Review 2026: Features, Pricing & Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$eLabFTW is a free, open-source electronic lab notebook for research teams. See 2026 self-hosting details, PRO support and hosting pricing, and top alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$eLabFTW is a free and open-source electronic laboratory notebook (ELN) built for experimental research teams that need to document protocols, track samples and reagents, and maintain an auditable, timestamped record of lab work. It was created by Nicolas Carpi, a research engineer at the Institut Curie in Paris, who first released the software around 2012 after finding that no adequate electronic notebook existed for his own day-to-day lab workflow. What began as a personal side project grew steadily in adoption across academic and research institutions, and by 2019 the project's popularity led Carpi to found Deltablot SASU, a company based in Paris, France, dedicated to supporting eLabFTW's ongoing development, professional support, and managed hosting.

eLabFTW is a web application written in PHP, released under the GNU Affero General Public License (AGPL), which guarantees that the source code and any modifications remain free and open even when the software is run as a network service. It is typically deployed via Docker, making self-hosted installation straightforward for institutional IT teams, and stores experiment data, file attachments, and metadata in a structured database that supports full version history and immutable timestamping of locked entries. The platform combines two core modules: an experiments module for documenting protocols, results, and observations in a rich-text, timestampable notebook, and a database/inventory module for cataloging samples, reagents, antibodies, cell lines, equipment, and other lab resources with custom metadata fields. Entries can be linked to each other, tagged, exported, and shared with collaborators, and the platform supports electronic signatures and audit logging to help labs meet reproducibility and compliance requirements such as those found in ISO 17025 or good laboratory practice environments.

Because eLabFTW is fully open source, there are no features locked behind a paywall: any lab with the technical capacity to self-host the software gets the complete feature set for free. Deltablot instead monetizes optional professional services layered on top of the free software. A PRO Support subscription, priced from EUR 760 per year, gives self-hosting institutions direct access to Deltablot's engineering team for troubleshooting, upgrades, and configuration help. For labs that prefer not to manage their own servers, Deltablot offers PRO Hosting, a fully managed cloud version of eLabFTW with automated backups, a custom domain, and infrastructure hosted in Europe, the United States, or Asia depending on customer preference, priced according to lab size and requirements. At the top of the range, PRO Hosting SecNumCloud, priced at EUR 6,985 per year, is a compliance-grade hosting tier built for organizations with strict data-sovereignty and security requirements, hosted exclusively in France by SecNumCloud-qualified providers and including encryption at rest, HDS health-data certification eligibility, and ISO 27001-aligned infrastructure.

eLabFTW's target users are academic research groups, university core facilities, biotech and pharmaceutical R&D teams, and government research institutions that need rigorous, auditable documentation of experimental work, often as a requirement for grant compliance, publication reproducibility, or regulatory audits. It has been adopted by numerous European universities and research computing centers, including deployments referenced by institutions such as Heidelberg University's computing center and the University of Graz, reflecting particularly strong adoption in academic settings across Germany, France, and Austria. Its main competitors include commercial electronic lab notebook platforms such as Benchling, LabArchives, RSpace, and SciNote, most of which are proprietary SaaS products with per-seat subscription pricing. eLabFTW differentiates itself as one of the only ELNs that is fully open source and free to self-host with zero feature restrictions, appealing especially to institutions with strong open-science principles, tight budgets, or strict requirements to keep experimental data on infrastructure they control. Notable facts include its academic origin story at a major cancer research institute, its AGPL licensing (a relatively strict open-source license chosen specifically to prevent closed-source forks from being offered as a service), and its growth from a single researcher's side project into a dedicated company serving research labs across Europe, North America, and beyond.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '40837e93-aef4-40d6-a619-0330eaa64ea6';

